Stories from UNODC

UNODC co-organizes meeting to counter drug trafficking in the Near and Middle
East

   UNODC co-organizes meeting against drug trafficking in the Near and
   Middle East

   Tashkent (Uzbekistan), 24 September 2019 - Representatives from 35
   countries and experts from over 20 international organizations met in
   Tashkent for the 54th Session of the Subcommission on Illicit Drug
   Traffic and Related Matters in the Near and Middle East, to strengthen
   cooperation in countering drug trafficking in these regions. The
   meeting, held from 23 to 27 September 2019, is co-organized by
   UNODC.[Read More]
   ***

Bolivia joins UNODC Blue Heart Campaign against human trafficking

   Bolivia joins UNODC Blue Heart Campaign against human trafficking

   Tarija (Bolivia), 23 September 2019 - Bolivia, through its Ministry of
   Foreign Affairs, joined the UNODC Blue Heart campaign to prevent and
   combat human trafficking on 20 September, during an event held in the
   Patio del Cabildo of the Municipality of Tarija.[Read More]
   ***

Uganda, UN and EU launch joint initiative to counter violent extremism in
prisons

   Uganda, UN and EU launch joint initiative to counter violent extremism
   in prisons

   20 September 2019 - On 10 September Uganda took an important step in
   addressing violent extremism in prisons by launching a four-year
   initiative under the programme "Supporting the management of violent
   extremist prisoners and the prevention of radicalization to violence in
   prisons." This initiative is supported by the United Nations, including
   the United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime, the European Union and
   the Government of the Netherlands.[Read More]
   ***
     * September 19, 2019 - Afghanistan joins UNODC global initiative
       against human trafficking and migrant smuggling
     * September 18, 2019 - UNODC and Mozambique discuss Strategic Roadmap
       against Crime, Drugs and Terrorism
     * September 17, 2019 - UNODC-supported Operation BENKADI tackles
       cross-border crime in Côte d’Ivoire, Mali and Burkina Faso

